allsearch_api.title: Swagger file does not conform to OpenAPI standard

comments.body:
Thanks for correcting the record, @Stranger6667, and for your offer to help !  Yeah, it seems that #168 didn't change the situation for me as far as running schemathesis.

* The following works fine: `st run --checks all swagger/v1/swagger.yaml --base-url https://allsearch-api.princeton.edu`.
* But when I try to run `st run --checks all https://allsearch-api.princeton.edu/api-docs/v1/swagger.yaml` (which should be the identical swagger.yaml file), I get:

```
Schema Loading Error

Received unsupported content while expecting a JSON or YAML payload for Open API

Tip: Verify that the URL points directly to the Open API schema
```

So it seems that there is something happening with either how schemathesis fetches the yaml file, or how we serve it?

Thank you for sharing the reproducing command!

The underlying error comes from the YAML parser:

```
unacceptable character #x0080: control characters are not allowed
  in "<unicode string>", position 758
```

It is here - `Theophile-Alexandre Steinlen, 1859\xe2\x80\x931923;`. It is raw content received from the network

I am going to adjust the error messages so it is easier to observe the underlying issue

Error Indexing cron: [pdc_discovery/staging] Net::ReadTimeout: Net::ReadTimeout with #<Socket:(closed)>

comments.body:
Disabling the DataSpace reindex did not fix the issue. I updated the post incident document (https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Rgc7KIlF9QVkPq8JHJl0JR-_kY7015O3dzde_RteGZk/edit) with my finding from today.

I noticed that although the commands that we issue to recreate the index (DELETE, CREATE) timed out and look like they did not succeeded, *as soon as I restarted one of the Solr nodes* they look like they actually succeeded 😱 -- i.e. the delete collection was gone and the created collection showed up in the Solr dashboard.

This issue happened again, it looks like heavy traffic to https://datacommons.princeton.edu/discovery/catalog/108913 (Shakespeare and Company Project Dataset: Lending Library Events)

What's strange is that this page is not even listed in the top 20 in Plausible:

![Screenshot 2023-12-01 at 4 04 25 PM](https://github.com/pulibrary/pdc_discovery/assets/568286/b1efa75f-ad76-4295-a46d-4c65832d36d1)
